text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!The Matched-guise test %0a%0a:Author: ahmed%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aAn Overview of the Matched-guise Test and its Applications in Sociolinguistics %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aSociolinguistics describes the study of how society (in all of its norms, cultural differences, expectations, etc) affects the way language is used in society. Sociolinguistics expectedly includes a degree of overlap with other parts of linguistics, such as pragmatics, linguistic anthropology, and the sociology of language (kind of a confusing term IMO but I digress). One important aspect of sociolinguistics involves determining how social attitudes or biases impact the way language is used within different communities or settings. The most common method in many sociolinguistic studies involves a structured interview with an individual related to the research subject at hand, however an experimental technique exists and is used to develop conclusions about language attitudes from different participants: the Matched-Guise test. %0a%0aThe test involves requiring listeners (the participants) to listen to what they believe are two different recordings of speakers of different languages and to form conclusions about certain traits about those speakers. Those traits include things such as intelligence, appearance, confidence, character, etc. The key part of the technique revolves around the fact that the recordings the participants listen to are actually produced by one speaker (a bilingual individual) and leads those participants to reach (oftentimes) different conclusions about the same speaker based on language. %0a%0aEthical objections to the Matched-Guise test have been long documented (specifically with the possible lack of informed consent) and contain limitations affected by the quality and performance of different dialects by the same individual, and how that is received by the listener. %0a%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matched-guise_test#Ethical_unacceptability%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sociolinguistics#Applications%0ahttps://www.cambridge.org/core/books/abs/research-methods-in-language-attitudes/matchedguise-technique/91729A40F9D2F2DA0F7B22DE61D3244B%0ahttps://eric.ed.gov/?id=ED367168%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 221206-222209-999550#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Matched Guise Test Criticism %0a-> - tiagocecchi1216%0a-> [-06.12.2022 - 14:22-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221206-222209-999550 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aThe Matched Guise Test is considered by many to be ethically unacceptable by modern standards. Contemporary ethical tests demand that the participant be fully informed about the test they are about to take and give their total consent. It has also been criticized for being ‘unnatural’; that is, participants are forced to give an answer rather than expressing their views freely. To this end, this attempt to expose covert attitudes may in fact be prompting the participants to express an opinion one way or the other, where no such opinion existed before. Indeed, these very criticisms were brought up by none other than the test’s creator, Wallace Lambert, in a paper published 12 years after the inception of the test.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221206-222209-999550#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:Section: E:)%0a(:Category: Varia:)%0a(:Title: The Matched-guise test :)
