diff:1670365329:1670105965:=57,71c57%0a%3c #foxbegin 221206-222209-999550#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Matched Guise Test Criticism %0a%3c -> - tiagocecchi1216%0a%3c -> [-06.12.2022 - 14:22-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221206-222209-999550 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c The Matched Guise Test is considered by many to be ethically unacceptable by modern standards. Contemporary ethical tests demand that the participant be fully informed about the test they are about to take and give their total consent. It has also been criticized for being ‘unnatural’; that is, participants are forced to give an answer rather than expressing their views freely. To this end, this attempt to expose covert attitudes may in fact be prompting the participants to express an opinion one way or the other, where no such opinion existed before. Indeed, these very criticisms were brought up by none other than the test’s creator, Wallace Lambert, in a paper published 12 years after the inception of the test.%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221206-222209-999550#%0a---%0a> %0a
